Liquid cooling has been around for years. What first sparked your interest in exploring it as a potential solution for Dropbox?
 Liquid cooling has been around for a while, and the industry has been actively experimenting with it. We‚Äôve followed the technology closely, including by attending conventions like the Open Compute Project summit where it‚Äôs a big topic. Bobby and I have seen these setups before and thought, this is really interesting‚Äîhow could we apply it to Dropbox? We‚Äôve had that question in the back of our minds for years now, and now we‚Äôre finally turning it into something concrete.
Bobby: Right. But it‚Äôs not as simple as just plugging in a liquid-cooled server. We need the right infrastructure in place so that if future high-performance servers require it, we‚Äôll be ready. This project was about building that foundation.
So the challenge you‚Äôre solving for is future-focused‚Äîpreparing for next-gen hardware and higher power needs?
 Exactly. It‚Äôs about handling both individual server power draw and the overall data center footprint. As new servers demand more power, sticking with only air cooling would force us to spread them out over more space. With liquid cooling, we can stay efficient‚Äîusing less space, less energy, and potentially lowering costs.
How might this technology fit into our current and future infrastructure strategy, particularly with respect to our focus on supporting AI workloads?
 We‚Äôre seeing a greater need today for new solutions, especially with GPUs and AI workloads. These systems draw a huge amount of power and generate significant heat. While vendors aren‚Äôt yet requiring liquid cooling for their top-tier GPUs, we know it‚Äôs on the horizon. Air cooling may soon only support mid-range options.
Daniel: And with Dropbox focusing more on AI initiatives, it gave us the push we needed. As we expand into GPU-heavy systems, it‚Äôs important to evaluate higher-powered setups. Hack Week was the perfect opportunity to explore that.


    
        
            
    

        

        
        
        

        
        
        

        
        

        
